-- EXHIBITIONS

By definition, assignment of receivables is the agreement by which the assignor creditor transmits to the assignee a claim against a third party. The position assumed by the curator (of the assigning creditor), to whom the public (the assigned debtor) owes the exhibition experience is transferred to the assignee (the visual artist), as the rightful owner and holder of the significant receivables. The exhibition “case” in question places the nature of significant claims in a personal identity spectrum – everyday experience, micro-narratives of the past, family experience, aspirations or opinions filtered and transitioned by the works of Andreea Gabriela Tudor. In other words, the expectant nature of the public’s positioning towards the presentation of the artistic act is subject to permanent negotiation, whilst the artistic corpus is being reduced as pretext and context of the identity transfer. The double instantiation and the conceptual contamination resulting from this juxtaposition underline the dialectical status of A.G. Tudor`s artworks, deconstructing the unidirectional artistic significance. The public has the freedom to configure its epistemic scaffolding around the works (validating and extracting value judgments), but it can also challenge, deny or discredit them. Thus, the present exhibition abandons teleological semantics in favor of „open-end meanings”.

The fundamental principle around which the artist builds the exhibition series refers to the experience of loneliness. Each work is generated starting from the premise of the moment of introspection, of the encounter with the self, foreshadowing a kaleidoscope of memories and identities. The characters and attitudes represented are avatars of a well-defined moment set in a personal chronology, transposed as hypothetical projections and artistic meta-discourses. The particular identity, memory and introspective exercise are hidden, adjusted, counterfeited and encrypted in such a way that they are not fundamentally equivalent to the artist`s persona. It rather questions and delimits archetypes and instances of the artist. Such elements of truthfulness (considered concrete and reality-anchors) that connect the visual corpora to the person, history and identity of A.G. Tudor are the photographs found in the work that documents the whole process of creation. Consequently, we deduce that the exhibition acquires Warburgian connotations – a trueBilderatlas Mnemosyne, scaled in accordance with the personal experience and the introspective methodology promoted by the artist. The idea of sequentially presenting the sources (underlined by A.G. Tudor in her personal statement: introspection-sleep-dream-death) is foreshadowed by the method of signage – each work is being placed in a pseudo-alveolus suggested by the architecture of the gallery. Although the experience targeted by the artworks is focused on the idea of close-proximity (or contact) with the intimate space of the artist`s identity (resulted from the way the artist perceives the world), the exhibition experience aims exceed this subjective limitation. Intimacy is clinically dissected and converted, transforming the gallery into a veritable laboratory of induced experiences. By shifting the focal point on the ideational transfer and on the artist-public relational formats, it is reaffirmed that contemporary creation has a prominent dialectical status. This debate fosters the permanent negotiation of meaning, role and functions of art.

Fortunately, art is not like law. If the exhibition experience does not involve relevance, interest, or does not achieve its stated purposes, the opposable third party, the assigned debtor (or the public, more specifically) has alternatives. If the present legal-artistic act does not satisfy the general interest, it can be sanctioned with absolute nullity; if it does not satisfy a particular interest, it may be sanctioned with relative nullity. In art, the adoption of such meanings and identities is not mandatory.', 'Although it has been grouped around a ubiquitous and personal theme (envisioning identity and its components), revolving around subjects regarding experience, memory and personal history, respectively – their transpositions into visual language, the artistic project <Assignments of identity claims> develops on two semantic complementary aspects: On the one hand, the visual (artistic) approach generating significant content involves a collection of stylistically and methodologically diverse corpora. Through them, Andreea Gabriela Tudor proposes a subjective excursion on her experiences, narratives and sources of inspiration, retrospective from the time frame in which they were made (2020-2022), but also prospective from the point of view of configuring her own artistic discourse. On the other hand, the curatorial approach aims at transferring these personal perspectives to the public, converting and assimilating them into a spectrum of immediate and unfiltered experience, phenomenon through which the identity factor (and by extension, the conceptual content) propagates and multiplies. Consequently, through the very title of the exhibition, the curatorial act presupposes the configuration of a so-called “true artistic jurisprudence”. Although the application of legal terminology to the artistic field may seem ironic (and to some extent, inappropriate), the “Brownian” diversity of current exhibition practices proves an acute need to establish set procedures and doctrines. This exhibition aims to lead by example how one can accomplish such ambitions.

