Fragile petals caress our skin, awakening within each of us a long-faded memory, a brief moment of respite in which our dearest experiences may be lived again. Like the shifting chromatic instances of the forget-me-not flower, the figures depicted by the two artists mirror, at varying intensities, subtle messages that create a dialogue between the echoes of our inner states and the emotions drawn viscerally from the soul. In this context, artistGabriela Tudorportrays figures imprisoned within amemento moridimension, the ephemerality of life sheltered within a corporeal vault that conceals a silent messenger of memories that never fade. The reverberation of the forget-me-not also extends to the portraits created by artistLavinia Oniciuc. Stepping timidly out of the dusk-laden gardens, the faces are (il)luminated by the promise of an idealized future, while the play of shadows awaits the unravelling of true human nature.

What does it mean to wither gradually within an impermanent reality, in the hope that one might reconcile the fragility and the power of memory? The exhibition—this sanctuary of the soul—awakens profound sentiments which, much like the forget-me-not flower, refuse to vanish, remaining vivid along the invisible thread of time.', 'Gardens have always functioned as spaces of refuge, where inward reflection is deepened by the patience and tranquility of nature, as human presence is enveloped by the eternal beauty of vegetal forms.The exhibitionForget-Me-Notevokes a horizon of memory—of enduring bonds woven into the fabric of existence—interpreted through two distinct chromatic approaches by artists Andreea Gabriela Tudor and Lavinia Maria Oniciuc.

Fragile petals caress our skin, awakening within each of us a long-faded memory, a brief moment of respite in which our dearest experiences may be lived again. Like the shifting chromatic instances of the forget-me-not flower, the figures depicted by the two artists mirror, at varying intensities, subtle messages that create a dialogue between the echoes of our inner states and the emotions drawn viscerally from the soul. In this context, artistGabriela Tudorportrays figures imprisoned within amemento moridimension, the ephemerality of life sheltered within a corporeal vault that conceals a silent messenger of memories that never fade. The reverberation of the forget-me-not also extends to the portraits created by artistLavinia Oniciuc. Stepping timidly out of the dusk-laden gardens, the faces are (il)luminated by the promise of an idealized future, while the play of shadows awaits the unravelling of true human nature.

