In a world of (over)accelerated interactions, it may not be the act of looking that truly matters, but rather the manner in which we draw near. To look affectively means not to seek a rational meaning within the image, but a sensation. It means allowing oneself to be touched by color, permitting pigment to move beyond vision and reach inward. Within the universe proposed by the artists, red becomes intensity and presence; yellow carries the light of a memory that still breathes; blue is the locus of silence; and violet projects a shadow that touches without causing pain. Thus, color—this omnipresent protagonist in the artists’ works—invites us to step into a space shaped by fragility, longing, absence, and proximity

Diana Păunescuopens this narrative with an incandescent painterly language. In her blazing reds, seemingly subjected to the conditions of a camera obscura, fragments of the body become a living substance, bearing the weight of unarticulated emotion.Georgiana-Geanina Susanuinvestigates the fragility and purity of the human being under the influence of environment and social pressures. Her figures render the tension between inner freedom and external constraint. By contrast, forCristiana-Emanuela Tărbuc, each brushstroke appears as a confessional gesture—an attempt to capture the light pulsing beneath the skin. Her bodies dissolve into light, as if molded from memory. Finally, dominated by cool tonalities, the works ofAndreea-Gabriela Tudorbring forth a sense of inner calm. Her figures oscillate between gesture and thought and, rendered in an almost oneiric manner, seem suspended within a state of temporal uncertainty.', 'The exhibitionPigments of Affective Contactbrings together four women artists who employ the body—their own or that of the other—as a territory for exploring emotion, memory, and vulnerability. In their works, skin becomes a site where color merges with memory, and the artistic act is transformed into a gesture of tenderness. Color, or pigment, functions as an extension of the human skin—an imprint of emotion that reaches the viewer through layers of sensitivity. Thus, the body no longer appears as a mere object to be looked at, but as an affective landscape in which the boundaries between the visible and the invisible are continuously redefined.

